comments.author: @DelTangBrav
comments.text:
Interesting experiment - it would be interesting to extend it to see if liking a video negates the dislike or has more effect than a dislike.
I was reading YouTube's explanations and apparently disliking a video is used to determine which videos are not suggested to you, not necessarily to overly criticise the video. It would appear that it's how many people actually register a like or dislike that really matters.
Too many mysteries surrounding YouTube's algorithms - YouTube will not reveal too much in case the knowledge is abused.

comments.author: @spiritusinfinitus
comments.text: Think of YouTube like a talk radio station.  They want people to listen so that they can play advertisements that the radio station earns revenue from to those people.  The radio station doesn't care if the people listening agree or disagree with the content.  All the care about is people listening to the station so they can be advertised at.  User engagement is what is important.  That user engagement can be positive or negative, it doesn't matter, they are still targets for the advertising.
